UML:TaggedValue.value: A StoryPattern represents a pattern, which can be viewed as a set of conditions. A condition is expressed over a set of variables, which can be bound or free. A pattern matcher is used to satisfy all the conditions by determining bindings for all free variables. The resulting subgraph that satisfies all conditions is referred to as a "match" for the pattern. For SDMs, "graph" patterns are used consisting of nodes (ObjectVariables) and edges (LInkVariables). Conditions are mainly structural, concerning the structure of the subgraph to be determined (types of nodes and edges). Non-structural constraints can currently be specified via Constraints (currently) only on ObjectVariables.

AttributeAssignments, although similar, are not really constraints and are thus treated separately in the metamodel.

UML:TaggedValue.value: An ObjectVariable represents a node in the storyPattern. It is a Variable and a TypedElement, and thus has a variableName, and a type that prescribes what kind of objects can be bound to the ObjectVariable in the pattern. A BindingOperator is used to specify what actions, if any, should be performed for the found binding (can be created, destroyed or just checked). The BindingSemantics defines how the binding can be constructed: if it is mandatory, optional or negative (No binding should be found). A BindingState is used to specify if the matches for the pattern are to be restrained by giving an apriori binding for the ObjectVariable (BOUND), or if the pattern matcher is free to determine a runtime binding for the ObjectVariable (UNBOUND).
